Strabo Geographgs: Mytilene has two harbours, of which the southern is landlocked and affords anchorage for fifty triremes, and the northern spacious and deep and protected by a breakwater. Both are flanked by a small island upon which part of the city is built. This city is well equipped with every convenience. Among famous Mytileneans of more ancient times are Pittacus, one of the Seven Sages, and the poet Alcaeus and his brother Anti- rnenidas1 . . . In those days, as the result of dis- sensions, the city was ruled from time to time by tyrants, who form the theme os the Political Songs, as they are called, of Alcaeus. The aforesaid Pittacus, being one of their number, did not escape the abuse of Alcaeus any more than the rest, Myrsilus, Melanchrus, the Cleanactids and others, although the poet was not free himself of the impu- tation of playing the revolutionary, while Pittacus made use of the monarchy only as a means of over- throwing arbitrary power and gave the city back its self-government as soon as his object was achieved.2
